---
import Canvas from "../layouts/Canvas.astro";
const styles = `
    .split-2 { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 16px; }
    @media (max-width: 900px) { .split-2 { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
    .product-card {
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: var(--radius-md);
      padding: 22px 22px 18px;
      background: var(--card);
    }
    .product-card h3 { font-size: 16px; margin: 0 0 4px; }
    .product-card .product-sub {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11px;
      color: var(--text-muted);
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.1em;
      margin-bottom: 14px;
    }
    .product-card ul { margin: 10px 0 0 0; padding-left: 18px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .product-card ul li { margin-bottom: 4px; }
    .step-row {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 36px 1fr;
      gap: 12px;
      padding: 12px 14px;
      border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
      border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
      background: var(--muted);
      margin-bottom: 8px;
    }
    .step-row .step-num {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 12px;
      color: var(--text-faint);
      padding-top: 2px;
    }
    .step-row .step-body { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-secondary); }
    .step-row .step-body strong { color: var(--text); }
    .code-inline { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 11.5px; background: var(--muted); padding: 2px 5px; border-radius: 3px; border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle); }
  `;
---

<Canvas title="11 · Checkout & Merchants — Sardis Canvas" currentId="checkout">
<Fragment slot="head">
  <style is:global set:html={styles}></style>
</Fragment>

<section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">Canvas 11 · Product</span>
        <h1>Checkout & Merchants</h1>
        <p class="hero-lead">
          The public repo keeps the checkout session engine, hardening migrations, API routes, and
          merchant SDK contracts. Hosted browser checkout UI and embed implementation live in the
          private product repo until Sardis deliberately publishes that widget as a stable OSS surface.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section" style="padding-top:0; border-top:0;">
        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <span class="callout-title">TL;DR</span>
          A merchant creates a <span class="code-inline">merchant_checkout_session</span>. A customer
          receives a <span class="code-inline">client_secret</span>, presents it to a checkout client,
          connects a wallet or uses a managed wallet path, signs a USDC transfer, and Sardis streams
          the outcome back. All public endpoints are <span class="code-inline">client_secret</span>-scoped
          so sessions cannot be enumerated and double-pay races cannot land.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Two products -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Products</div>
          <h2>One session engine, two front doors.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Both products create rows in the same <code>merchant_checkout_sessions</code> table and emit
            the same webhook envelope. The difference is who holds the wallet and where the crypto knobs live.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="split-2">
          <div class="product-card">
            <div class="product-sub">Pay with Sardis</div>
            <h3>Crypto-native checkout — customer brings the wallet.</h3>
            <p class="text-muted" style="font-size:13px;">
              Drop-in checkout, similar in shape to Stripe Checkout but paying in USDC. Customer connects
              MetaMask / Coinbase Wallet / any WalletConnect provider, or fiat-onramps into a fresh wallet
              via Coinbase CDP. Settlement lands on the merchant's configured address (or connected merchant bank
              account for USD payout).
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>Client-secret-scoped API for browser or server checkout clients</li>
              <li>External wallet confirmation and server-managed payment paths</li>
              <li>Optional onramp integration for fiat-first customers</li>
              <li>EIP-191 signature binds payer wallet to session</li>
              <li>SSE stream for real-time status in the merchant UI</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="product-card">
            <div class="product-sub">Sardis Connect</div>
            <h3>Zero-crypto merchant SDK — three lines of code.</h3>
            <p class="text-muted" style="font-size:13px;">
              For API providers who want to charge AI agents without ever touching a chain.
              <code>@sardis/connect</code> wraps an Express/Next.js route, serves a
              <code>/.well-known/sardis.json</code> manifest, and reports usage to Sardis. The merchant
              sees a USD balance; Sardis handles wallet creation, settlement, and payout.
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><code>packages/sardis-connect</code> (Python) · <code>packages/sardis-connect-js</code> (TS)</li>
              <li><code>PricedEndpoint</code> / <code>UsageRecord</code> / <code>ServiceManifest</code> models</li>
              <li>Protocol-agnostic: <code>accepts: ["sardis", "x402", "mpp"]</code></li>
              <li>Per-call, per-unit, and subscription pricing tiers</li>
              <li>Payout via connected merchant bank · no wallet UX on the merchant side</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Pay with Sardis flow -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Pay with Sardis · End-to-end</div>
          <h2>Seven steps from merchant intent to settled USDC.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Every step corresponds to a real endpoint in
            <code>apps/api/server/routes/commerce/merchant_checkout.py</code>. Public endpoints
            live under the <code>/sessions/client/&#123;client_secret&#125;/...</code> namespace; merchant endpoints
            require a principal.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="step-row">
            <div class="step-num">01</div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <strong>Merchant creates session.</strong>
              <code>POST /v1/merchant/checkout/sessions</code> (authenticated with merchant principal) →
              inserts a row into <code>merchant_checkout_sessions</code> with amount, currency, chain,
              settlement target, optional <code>idempotency_key</code> and <code>embed_origin</code>.
              Server generates a <code>client_secret</code> (24 random bytes, base64).
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step-row">
            <div class="step-num">02</div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <strong>Redirect or embed.</strong>
              Merchant passes the <code>client_secret</code> to a checkout client. Hosted UI is product-private;
              the public contract is the client-secret-scoped session API and the webhook/SSE contract.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step-row">
            <div class="step-num">03</div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <strong>Checkout client loads session.</strong>
              A browser, mobile, or server checkout client fetches
              <code>GET /sessions/client/&#123;client_secret&#125;/details</code> — returns the amount, merchant name,
              and the <code>settlement_address</code> needed for client-side USDC transfers.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step-row">
            <div class="step-num">04</div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <strong>Wallet connect.</strong>
              Customer connects via wagmi. Two paths converge here:
              external wallet (<code>POST /connect-external</code>, EIP-191 signature verified server-side)
              or CDP Onramp (<code>GET /onramp-token</code>, fiat → USDC in a fresh wallet). Either way,
              <code>payer_wallet_address</code> is persisted on the session.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step-row">
            <div class="step-num">05</div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <strong>Payment.</strong>
              Customer signs a USDC <code>transfer</code> to <code>settlement_address</code>. Frontend
              submits via viem; server records the tx hash via
              <code>POST /confirm-external-payment</code>. Session flips <code>pending → confirmed</code>.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step-row">
            <div class="step-num">06</div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <strong>Streaming update.</strong>
              Merchant systems and checkout clients subscribe to
              <code>GET /sessions/client/&#123;client_secret&#125;/stream</code> (SSE). Polling fallback at
              <code>.../details</code> exists for clients that can't hold an SSE connection.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step-row">
            <div class="step-num">07</div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <strong>Settlement + webhook.</strong>
              Background job reconciles the on-chain receipt, computes
              <code>platform_fee_amount</code> and <code>net_amount</code>, flips status to
              <code>settled</code>, and enqueues a <code>checkout.session.settled</code> webhook. Delivery
              is tracked in <code>merchant_webhook_deliveries</code> keyed by <code>event_id</code> for
              dedup.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Session lifecycle Mermaid -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">State machine</div>
          <h2>Merchant checkout session lifecycle.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            The session row moves through a narrow set of states. Every transition is audited; every
            terminal state triggers a webhook.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> created : POST /merchant/checkout/sessions
    created --> pending : client loads /s/{client_secret}
    pending --> expired : TTL elapsed
    pending --> connected : connect-external (EIP-191 verified)
    pending --> connected : onramp-token (CDP, payer wallet bound)
    connected --> confirmed : confirm-external-payment (tx hash)
    confirmed --> settled : reconciliation job · receipt verified
    settled --> paid_out : connected merchant bank transfer (if USD payout)
    pending --> failed : signature / balance / policy rejection
    confirmed --> failed : tx reverted on-chain
    settled --> [*]
    paid_out --> [*]
    expired --> [*]
    failed --> [*]
          </pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Hardening -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Hardening</div>
          <h2>Why public checkout is boring in a good way.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            <code>apps/api/migrations/031_checkout_hardening.sql</code> is the migration that
            turned Pay with Sardis from "it works on the happy path" into something safe to point at the
            open internet. Polar-inspired; every column earns its keep.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Control</th><th>Column / Table</th><th>What it prevents</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Client secret</td>
              <td><code>merchant_checkout_sessions.client_secret</code> (UNIQUE)</td>
              <td>Session ID enumeration. Public endpoints use <code>/sessions/client/&#123;client_secret&#125;/...</code>, never the internal UUID.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Idempotency key</td>
              <td><code>merchant_checkout_sessions.idempotency_key</code> (UNIQUE, partial)</td>
              <td>Duplicate session creation on merchant-side retry. DB-level uniqueness, not app-level.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Row lock on pay</td>
              <td><code>SELECT ... FOR UPDATE NOWAIT</code> in the pay path</td>
              <td>Double-pay races when a customer clicks twice or two tabs submit simultaneously.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Embed origin</td>
              <td><code>merchant_checkout_sessions.embed_origin</code></td>
              <td>Clickjacking / hostile iframe. Hosted clients must restrict <code>postMessage</code> to the declared origin.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Webhook dedup</td>
              <td><code>merchant_webhook_deliveries.event_id</code> (UNIQUE)</td>
              <td>Double-processing on retries. Merchants can safely use at-least-once delivery.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Fee transparency</td>
              <td><code>platform_fee_amount</code> · <code>net_amount</code></td>
              <td>"Why did I get less than I charged?" support tickets. Full breakdown on every session.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Reusable links</td>
              <td><code>merchant_checkout_links</code> table</td>
              <td>One-off sessions for static storefronts; merchant generates a slug, Sardis creates a fresh session per visitor.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Payer binding</td>
              <td><code>payer_wallet_address</code> (migration 033)</td>
              <td>Wrong-wallet payment. The onramp token endpoint validates the wallet matches the session binding.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Hosted client boundary -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Hosted client boundary</div>
          <h2>What remains private vs. public.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            The public repo documents and tests the backend contract. The hosted React checkout client,
            visual design, and embeddable script are product code and should be recovered into the
            private product repo from git history if needed.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Public contract</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <ul style="margin:0; padding-left:18px;">
                <li>Session creation and lookup endpoints.</li>
                <li>Client-secret-scoped public session operations.</li>
                <li>SSE status stream and webhook event envelope.</li>
                <li>Database idempotency, deduplication, and settlement state.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Private product surface</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <ul style="margin:0; padding-left:18px;">
                <li>Hosted browser checkout UI.</li>
                <li>Embeddable script and web component.</li>
                <li>Conversion, analytics, branding, and merchant dashboard loops.</li>
                <li>Provider-specific wallet UX decisions.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- CDP Onramp + external wallet -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Two ways to fund a payment</div>
          <h2>External wallet · CDP Onramp.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Customers either already own crypto (external wallet path) or don't (CDP Onramp path).
            Both converge at the same session state: a verified <code>payer_wallet_address</code> with
            enough USDC to settle.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">External wallet — EIP-191 binding</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Frontend: wagmi + viem + WalletConnect v2 + Coinbase Wallet SDK.
              Flow: <code>GET /connect-params</code> returns the challenge to sign, customer signs with
              wallet, frontend posts signature to <code>POST /connect-external</code>. Server verifies
              the EIP-191 signature recovers the claimed address and persists it as
              <code>payer_wallet_address</code>. On pay, customer signs the actual USDC transfer;
              frontend reports the hash via <code>POST /confirm-external-payment</code>.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">CDP Onramp — fiat to USDC</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              For customers without crypto. Sardis mints an MPC wallet for the session, calls
              <code>POST api.developer.coinbase.com/onramp/v1/token</code> with a CDP JWT, and returns a
              hosted <code>pay.coinbase.com/buy/select-asset</code> URL bound to that wallet.
              The <code>/onramp-token</code> endpoint validates the wallet address matches the
              session — an attacker cannot redirect funds to a different wallet by tampering with the
              query string.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Sardis Connect -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Sardis Connect</div>
          <h2>Three lines of middleware, zero crypto on the merchant side.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Sardis Connect is the opposite philosophy to Pay with Sardis. The merchant never sees a wallet,
            never sees chain config, never handles stablecoin balances. They wrap their API with
            <code>sardisConnect(&#123; apiKey &#125;)</code>, declare pricing, and get USD in their connected merchant bank
            account. Sardis absorbs the crypto layer entirely.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Merchant code — TypeScript</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <pre class="code-block"><code>import &#123; sardisConnect &#125; from '@sardis/connect';
const sardis = sardisConnect(&#123; apiKey: 'mch_live_xxx' &#125;);
app.use(sardis.middleware());</code></pre>
              The middleware reads a priced endpoint manifest, rejects unpaid calls with
              <code>402 Payment Required</code> (x402-compatible), and forwards paid calls to the merchant
              handler. Protocol-agnostic: one middleware accepts Sardis native, x402, and MPP.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Service manifest</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Served at <code>/.well-known/sardis.json</code> — agents discover pricing via
              <code>ServiceManifest</code>:
              <ul style="margin:6px 0 0; padding-left:18px;">
                <li><code>PricedEndpoint(path, method, price, pricing_model)</code></li>
                <li><code>pricing_model</code>: <code>per_call</code> · <code>per_unit</code> · <code>subscription</code></li>
                <li><code>UsageRecord</code> for metered billing (report units after the call)</li>
                <li>Tiered pricing via <code>PricingTier</code></li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Merchant trust + checkout controls -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Risk + merchant-side controls</div>
          <h2>Trust scoring and the merchant kill switch.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Two pieces of machinery sit next to the session engine: per-merchant trust profiles (Sardis
            decides how much to trust the merchant) and checkout controls (the merchant decides what
            shape of payments to accept).
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Merchant trust — migration 045</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <code>merchant_trust_profiles</code> stores <code>trust_level</code>, a rolling
              <code>trust_score</code> (default 0.3), <code>transaction_count</code>,
              <code>total_volume</code>, and <code>dispute_count</code>. <code>MerchantTrustService</code>
              adjusts approval thresholds: first-seen merchants face stricter KYC + lower velocity caps,
              merchants with a dispute history get flagged for manual review. Verified merchants
              (<code>verified_at</code>, <code>verified_by</code>) get the tightest loop.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Checkout controls router</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <code>apps/api/server/routes/commerce/checkout_controls.py</code> exposes
              merchant-side knobs: amount caps, country allowlists, velocity limits, required
              customer-KYC tier. <code>GET /config</code> / <code>PUT /config</code> for configuration,
              <code>POST /incidents</code> / <code>GET /incidents</code> for the merchant's audit trail of
              auto-blocked or flagged sessions.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Surface -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Endpoint surface</div>
          <h2>What's actually wired up.</h2>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Endpoint</th><th>Auth</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>POST /v1/merchant/checkout/sessions</code></td><td>Merchant principal</td><td>Create session (idempotent via <code>idempotency_key</code>).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GET /v1/merchant/checkout/sessions/&#123;id&#125;</code></td><td>Merchant principal</td><td>Inspect session from merchant side.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GET /sessions/client/&#123;client_secret&#125;/details</code></td><td>Public</td><td>Session detail for the checkout iframe.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GET /sessions/client/&#123;client_secret&#125;/connect-params</code></td><td>Public</td><td>Challenge for EIP-191 signature.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /sessions/client/&#123;client_secret&#125;/connect-external</code></td><td>Public</td><td>Bind external wallet via EIP-191 signature.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /sessions/client/&#123;client_secret&#125;/pay</code></td><td>Public</td><td>Server-signed pay path (Sardis-managed wallet).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /sessions/client/&#123;client_secret&#125;/confirm-external-payment</code></td><td>Public</td><td>Client-signed USDC transfer; record tx hash.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GET /sessions/client/&#123;client_secret&#125;/balance</code></td><td>Public</td><td>Live balance read for the funded wallet.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GET /sessions/client/&#123;client_secret&#125;/stream</code></td><td>Public</td><td>SSE stream for status transitions.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /sessions/client/&#123;client_secret&#125;/onramp-token</code></td><td>Public</td><td>CDP Onramp URL bound to payer wallet.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /merchants/&#123;id&#125;/links</code> · <code>GET /merchants/&#123;id&#125;/links</code></td><td>Merchant principal</td><td>Reusable checkout links (<code>merchant_checkout_links</code>).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>POST /stripe-connect/...</code> (3 routes)</td><td>Merchant principal</td><td>Onboarding + payout target for USD settlement.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GET/PUT /checkout-controls/config</code></td><td>Merchant principal</td><td>Velocity / country / amount / KYC controls.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Source of truth -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Source of truth</div>
          <h2>Files to grep when something looks off.</h2>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>File</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>apps/api/server/routes/commerce/merchant_checkout.py</code></td><td>All <code>/sessions/...</code> endpoints: create, connect, pay, confirm, stream, onramp.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>apps/api/server/routes/commerce/checkout.py</code></td><td>Legacy /checkout surface used by older integrations; kept for backwards compat.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>apps/api/server/routes/commerce/merchants.py</code></td><td>Merchant CRUD + checkout links + settlements lookup.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>apps/api/server/routes/commerce/checkout_controls.py</code></td><td>Merchant-side controls + incident log.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>apps/api/server/routes/providers/stripe_connect.py</code></td><td>connected merchant bank onboarding for USD payout.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>apps/api/migrations/031_checkout_hardening.sql</code></td><td>client_secret · idempotency · embed_origin · checkout_links · webhook_deliveries.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>apps/api/migrations/033_wallet_verification.sql</code></td><td><code>payer_wallet_address</code> column + <code>external_wallet</code> payment method.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>apps/api/migrations/045_merchant_trust.sql</code></td><td><code>merchant_trust_profiles</code> scoring table.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-checkout/src/sardis_checkout/</code></td><td>Orchestrator · sessions · webhooks · settlement · fraud · idempotency · partial payments.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-connect/src/sardis_connect/</code></td><td>Python merchant SDK · models · middleware.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>packages/sardis-connect-js/src/</code></td><td>TypeScript merchant SDK · <code>middleware.ts</code> · <code>types.ts</code>.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Cross-refs -->
      <section class="section">
